	<h1 id="firstHeading" class="firstHeading" lang="en">Bluebeard</h1>
	<div id="bodyContent" class="mw-body-content">
		<div id="siteSub" class="noprint">From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia</div>
		<div id="contentSub"></div>
		<div id="contentSub2"></div>
		
		<div id="jump-to-nav"></div>
		<a class="mw-jump-link" href="#mw-head">Jump to navigation</a>
		<a class="mw-jump-link" href="#searchInput">Jump to search</a>
		<div id="mw-content-text" lang="en" dir="ltr" class="mw-content-ltr"><div class="mw-parser-output"><div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable">For other uses, see <a href="/wiki/Bluebeard_(disambiguation)" class="mw-disambig" title="Bluebeard (disambiguation)">Bluebeard (disambiguation)</a>.</div>
<div class="shortdescription nomobile noexcerpt noprint searchaux" style="display:none">French folktale</div>
<table class="infobox" style="width:22em"><tbody><tr><th colspan="2" style="text-align:center;font-size:125%;font-weight:bold;color: #000000; background-color: #cef2e0;">Bluebeard</th></tr><tr><td colspan="2" style="text-align:center"><a href="/wiki/File:Blue_Beard_in_Tales_of_Mother_Goose_(Welsh).png" class="image"><img alt="Blue Beard in Tales of Mother Goose (Welsh).png" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/6d/Blue_Beard_in_Tales_of_Mother_Goose_%28Welsh%29.png/220px-Blue_Beard_in_Tales_of_Mother_Goose_%28Welsh%29.png" decoding="async" width="220" height="299" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/6d/Blue_Beard_in_Tales_of_Mother_Goose_%28Welsh%29.png/330px-Blue_Beard_in_Tales_of_Mother_Goose_%28Welsh%29.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/6d/Blue_Beard_in_Tales_of_Mother_Goose_%28Welsh%29.png/440px-Blue_Beard_in_Tales_of_Mother_Goose_%28Welsh%29.png 2x" data-file-width="1517" data-file-height="2065" /></a><div>Bluebeard gives his wife the keys to his castle.</div></td></tr><tr><th colspan="2" style="text-align:center">Folk tale</th></tr><tr><th scope="row">Name</th><td>Bluebeard</td></tr><tr><th scope="row">Also known as</th><td>Barbebleue</td></tr><tr><th colspan="2" style="text-align:center">Data</th></tr><tr><th scope="row"><a href="/wiki/Aarne%E2%80%93Thompson_classification_system" class="mw-redirect" title="Aarne–Thompson classification system">Aarne-Thompson</a> grouping</th><td>ATU 312 (The Bluebeard, The Maiden-Killer)</td></tr><tr><th scope="row">Region</th><td><a href="/wiki/France" title="France">France</a></td></tr><tr><th scope="row">Published in</th><td><i><a href="/wiki/Histoires_ou_contes_du_temps_pass%C3%A9" title="Histoires ou contes du temps passé">Histoires ou contes du temps passé</a></i>, by <a href="/wiki/Charles_Perrault" title="Charles Perrault">Charles Perrault</a></td></tr><tr><th scope="row">Related</th><td><a href="/wiki/The_Robber_Bridegroom_(fairy_tale)" title="The Robber Bridegroom (fairy tale)">The Robber Bridegroom</a>; <a href="/wiki/How_the_Devil_Married_Three_Sisters" title="How the Devil Married Three Sisters">How the Devil Married Three Sisters</a>; <a href="/wiki/Fitcher%27s_Bird" title="Fitcher&#39;s Bird">Fitcher's Bird</a></td></tr></tbody></table>
<p>"<b>Bluebeard</b>" (<a href="/wiki/French_language" title="French language">French</a>: <i lang="fr">Barbe bleue</i>, <small></small><span title="Representation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)" class="IPA"><a href="/wiki/Help:IPA/French" title="Help:IPA/French">[baʁbə blø]</a></span>) is a French <a href="/wiki/Folklore" title="Folklore">folktale</a>, the most famous surviving version of which was written by <a href="/wiki/Charles_Perrault" title="Charles Perrault">Charles Perrault</a> and first published by Barbin in Paris in 1697 in <i><a href="/wiki/Histoires_ou_contes_du_temps_pass%C3%A9" title="Histoires ou contes du temps passé">Histoires ou contes du temps passé</a></i>.<sup id="cite_ref-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-1">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-2">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> The tale tells the story of a wealthy man in the habit of murdering his wives and the attempts of one wife to avoid the fate of her predecessors. "<a href="/wiki/The_White_Dove_(French_fairy_tale)" title="The White Dove (French fairy tale)">The White Dove</a>", "<a href="/wiki/The_Robber_Bridegroom_(fairy_tale)" title="The Robber Bridegroom (fairy tale)">The Robber Bridegroom</a>" and "<a href="/wiki/Fitcher%27s_Bird" title="Fitcher&#39;s Bird">Fitcher's Bird</a>" (also called "Fowler's Fowl") are tales similar to "Bluebeard".<sup id="cite_ref-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-3">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-wdove_4-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-wdove-4">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup> The notoriety of the tale is such that <a href="/wiki/Merriam-Webster" title="Merriam-Webster">Merriam-Webster</a> gives the word "Bluebeard" the definition of "a man who marries and kills one wife after another," and the verb "bluebearding" has even appeared as a way to describe the crime of either killing a series of women, or seducing and abandoning a series of women.<sup id="cite_ref-5" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-5">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
